whats_good: The excitated state decay and the RuIII formation are resoanble across the runs
whats_bad:
Formation of Rudimer across the runs only from RuIII species, not through reaction of RuIII species and RuII
In several runs including of radical sepcies, without side reactions of these reactive species
In majority of runs low quantum yields for exciation of RuII
In majority of runs very fast intial oxygen formation, than steady decline, unlike the experimental data
In majority of runs very fast oxidative quenching of excitated RuII species
suggested_actions:
Include deactivation through reaction from RuIII and RuII
Enforce high quantum yield for exciation of RuII
Enforce slower intial oxygen formation, maybe by testing for global maximum for the found O2 rate

whats_good:
The excitated state decay fits well for the runs
The formation of RuIII is also reasonable for most runs
The formation of H2O2 from H2O and RuIII is reasonable for the runs
The form of the kinetic traces is mostly in good agreement with the experimental data
whats_bad:
The quantum yield for the RuII excitation is quite low most of the runs
The formation of dimerization is often quite slow
The trend for the Ru concentration dependency is in all runs wrong (no maximum observable, but steady increase or plateu)
suggested_actions:
Enforce high quantum yield for RuII excitation
Include deactivation through reaction from RuIII and RuII
Weigh correct form of Ru concentration dependency higher
Test dark O2 formation reactions

whats_good: The decay of RuII_ex, formation of RuIII, light and dark H2O2 reactions are all reasonable for most runs
whats_bad:
In most runs reaction of SO4 with RuII present, which does not occur
Dimierization typically only from RuIII species
Shape of kinetic traces is typically wrong for high Ruthenium and S2O8 concentrations
Partially low quantum yield for RuII exciation
Often reaction of RuIII with RuII_ex yielding two RuII (does not fit from oxidation numbers)
suggested_actions:
Remove reaction of SO4 with RuII
Remove reaction of RuIII with RuII_ex
Enforce high quantum yield for RuII excitaiton
Add reaction of Ru_dimer with RuIII to further Ru_dimers

whats_good:
Excitiation, relaxation, H2O2 formation, oxidative quenching look reasonable in most runs
Trends for irradiance and Na2S2O8 dependencies typically good
whats_bad:
Partially highly unlikely reactions, e.g. Reactions with non exsiting reagents, reactions between 3 or more components
Trend for Ru concentration dependency qualitively wrong in most runs
Generally O2 formation rate is understimated in most runs for the vast majority of conditions
suggested_actions:
Reduce amount of similar reactions when possible
Try to implement decreased activity at higher Ru concnetrations, e.g. by slow autocatalytic deactivation formed Ru_dimer with RuIII species

The self quenching and excitated state decay are realsitc on all runs
dark and light driven oxidative quenching are mostly realsitc

Often low quantum yield for excitation of RuII

Dimer decomposes in different species in several runs
The forms of the kinetic fits is typically not correct for specific conditions: espacially at high Ru concentrations, as well as high S2O8 concentraions the fit does not fit to the experimental data
suggested_actions:
Enforce high quantum yield for RuII excitation
Try to introduce pH influence also for dark reaction
Add autocatalytic deactivation of RuIII with formed Ru_dimer
Add goodness of fit to kinetic traces to feedback function

whats_good:
* Run 2 and Run 3 give decent fits to underlying rate data
* Run 3 captures trends other than [Ru] dependence quite well
* The mechanism for run 3 is quite reasonable
whats_bad:
* Multiple runs do not fit the underlying rate data correctly (likely numerical instability of model) - runs 1, 4 and 5 are completely unusable
*Most runs do not capture [Ru] catalyst dependence correctly (rate does not go down with increasing concentration)
* Run 2 captures light dependence trend incorrectly.
suggested_actions:
* For model from run 3: including autocatalytic [Ru] decomposition to obtain correct [Ru] dependence
* For model from run 2: removing unnecessary steps, such as quenching of two excited RuII (very unlikely), radical recombination is also unlikely

* Fixing underlying rate fit for model from run 3
